<TITLE>Letter to the editor: Internet use tax collection tough on small businesses</TITLE>


<TEXT>
While I <EVENT eid="e1" class="I_ACTION">agree</EVENT> with Norman McNickles basic concept of collecting internet use tax, his article was clearly one-sided and he has apparently never had the experience of being <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">involved</EVENT> in online sales ("State law to <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">collect</EVENT> internet use tax is toothless," <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2017-01-19">Jan. 19</TIMEX3>).

As a small-business owner I am <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">involved</EVENT> in both local sales and online sales. I have no problem with <EVENT eid="e5" class="I_ACTION">collecting</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">remitting</EVENT> Oklahoma state sales tax. There is a handy online application that I <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">use</EVENT> and it takes me about <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DURATION" value="PTXH">an hour</TIMEX3> to <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">total</EVENT> up the monthly sales and <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">remit</EVENT> the tax.

Posted in Letters on <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2017-01-29">Sunday</TIMEX3>, Ja
</TEXT>


